\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,g(x))=0$
\end_inset

.
 The implicit function theorem shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{x}f(x,g(x))+D_{y}f(x,g(x))Dg(x)=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{x}f$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $Dg(x)$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 We note that the formula can be obtained from taking derivative on both
 sides with respective to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes, taking derivatives on the both sides can greatly simplify calculatio
ns.
 Here are some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}=\argmin_{x\in\Rn}f_{t}(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 are strictly convex.
 Then, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx_{t}}{dt}=(\nabla^{2}f_{t}(x_{t}))^{-1}\nabla\frac{df_{t}}{dt}(x_{t}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By the optimality condition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f_{t}(x_{t})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Taking derivatives on both sides, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}f_{t}(x_{t})\frac{dx_{t}}{dt}+\nabla\frac{df_{t}}{dt}(x_{t})=0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 are strictly convex, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}f_{t}(x_{t})$
\end_inset

 is positive definite and is invertible.
 Hence, we have that the result.
\end_layout

